## Confluence Page 2: AKS Log Shipping
```
Page Title: Log Shipping | AKS → Fluent Bit → Splunk HEC
Parent:     Platform Engineering / Observability / Log Shipping
Labels:     fluent-bit, splunk, aks, kubernetes, helm, terraform
```

***
### Overview
This page documents the solution for shipping logs from Azure Kubernetes Service (AKS) clusters directly to Splunk using **Fluent Bit** deployed as a **Kubernetes DaemonSet** via Helm.

| Property | Value |
|----------|-------|
| **Log Shipper** | Fluent Bit 3.2.7 |
| **Deployment Method** | Helm DaemonSet (one pod per node) |
| **Helm Chart** | `fluent/fluent-bit` v0.46.7 |
| **Namespace** | `logging` |
| **Destination** | Splunk HEC `:8088` |
| **Splunk Index** | `aks-logs` |
| **Clusters** | 20 AKS clusters |
| **Status** | ✅ Production |

> ⚠️ **Azure VM Extensions are NOT supported on AKS nodes.** AKS nodes are fully managed by Azure. Fluent Bit must be deployed via Helm DaemonSet only.

***
### Architecture
> *(Attach diagram_aks.png here)*

```
AKS Cluster (x20)
  └── Node 1 → Fluent Bit Pod (DaemonSet) ──┐
  └── Node 2 → Fluent Bit Pod (DaemonSet) ──┤→ Splunk HEC :8088
  └── Node N → Fluent Bit Pod (DaemonSet) ──┘  (index=aks-logs)
       ↑
  Helm values.yaml
  (deployed by Terraform for_each)
```

***
### Log Sources Collected
| Source | Path | Tag | Notes |
|--------|------|-----|-------|
| All container logs | `/var/log/containers/*.log` | `kube.*` | stdout + stderr |
| Kubernetes metadata | API Server | enriched | pod name, namespace, labels |

**Enriched fields added per log entry:**
- `cluster` — cluster name (injected per `for_each` iteration)
- `source` — `azure-aks`
- `index` — `aks-logs`
- `kubernetes.pod_name`
- `kubernetes.namespace_name`
- `kubernetes.labels`

***
### Terraform Module Structure
```
modules/
├── fluentbit-aks/
│   ├── main.tf          ← helm_release resource (for_each over clusters)
│   └── variables.tf     ← Inputs: aks_clusters map, splunk_hec_*
└── aks/
    └── main.tf          ← YOUR EXISTING MODULE (add data + module call)
```

**Scaling:** `for_each` over `aks_clusters` map.
Adding a new cluster = it is auto-discovered from `data.azurerm_kubernetes_cluster`.

***
### Required Variables (`terraform.tfvars`)
```hcl
splunk_hec_host  = "splunk.yourcompany.com"
splunk_hec_port  = 8088
splunk_hec_token = "xxxx-xxxx-xxxx-xxxx"   # from Splunk UI

cluster_names = [
  "aks-prod-01",
  "aks-prod-02",
  # ... up to 20
]
```

***
### Deployment Steps
1. Enable Splunk HEC → create token and index `aks-logs`
2. Add `splunk_hec_*` variables to `terraform.tfvars`
3. Add `data` block + module call to `modules/aks/main.tf`
4. Add Helm provider to `providers.tf`
5. Run `terraform init && terraform plan && terraform apply`
6. Verify DaemonSet on each cluster

***
### Verification Commands
```bash
# Check DaemonSet is running on all nodes
kubectl get ds -n logging fluent-bit

# Check all pods are Running (should equal node count)
kubectl get pods -n logging -o wide

# Watch live logs from Fluent Bit
kubectl logs -n logging -l app.kubernetes.io/name=fluent-bit -f

# Health check endpoint
kubectl port-forward -n logging ds/fluent-bit 2020:2020
curl http://localhost:2020/api/v1/health

# Generate test log
kubectl run test-log --image=busybox --rm -it --restart=Never \
  -- sh -c "for i in \$(seq 1 5); do echo 'splunk test log'; sleep 1; done"

# Splunk search
index=aks-logs source=azure-aks
index=aks-logs cluster=aks-prod-01
```

***
### Troubleshooting
| Symptom | Cause | Fix |
|---------|-------|-----|
| Pods not scheduled on all nodes | Missing toleration | Add master/control-plane toleration |
| `Permission denied` on log files | RBAC missing | Ensure `rbac.create=true` in Helm values |
| No logs in Splunk | HEC token wrong | Check `Splunk_Token` in Helm config |
| OOMKilled pods | Memory limit too low | Increase `limits.memory` to `512Mi` |
| Duplicate logs | Multiple DaemonSets | Check only one Fluent Bit release per cluster |

